description.text:
This is my first built from scratch 3d model. My inspiration came from the Millennium Falcon and the Outrider from Shadows of the Empire. I used Tinkercad and scaled it to match Bandai's 1/144th Millennium Falcon. As it is my 1st build I made a few mistakes. The only one that matters to me is that the engine is a mm or 2 higher than it should be, but since its star wars and symmetry is unheard of in that galaxy, I suspect it only adds to its appeal lol.

I designed the ship to be detailed after printing with plasticard and 3d printed greeblies, thus the lack of surface detail. There are 2 versions, one without the ramp and one with the ramp.

I have uploaded many different printable configurations. The one pictured was Printed on the mp mini v2, which has a 4x4x4 build surface. Built in 8 pieces.

The landing gear was remixed from this creators files (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2500827). Build 4 of them.

Update. I added a much more detailed version of the ship using files from these 2 creators (https://www.myminifactory.com/object/star-wars-millennium-falcon-hasbro-missing-details-51628), (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2609670), and guns from this creator (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2535503/#files). The guns will need support.

I made a dish for it, I printed it with support, touching build plate only, using cura. You will need to sand a little, as its a friction fit. The landing bay doors are also friction fit but I did not need to sand them. I was going to make the guns friction fit as well but there so small I figured I would either glue them on or use wire to mount them. Both halves of the ship were printed with 8% infill, 1.2mm thick walls, and without support, with only a few places with filament droop. Mainly the docking rings and the forks, all easily fixed with a little sanding or cutting.
I have still not figured out how to add armor plates to the ships round sections and plan to use .010 plastic sheet to add them instead. here's a link to the plastic I'll be using, (https://www.ebay.com/itm/Package-of-4-WHITE-STYRENE-PLASTIC-SHEET-010-THICK-8-X-12/272700619143?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649)

description.text:
These cubes that I made in Rhino are representations of the 3D Hilbert Curve concept. There are printable files of the first, second, and third iterations of the curve. As It is an infinite family of curves, I have a program that I wrote to draw the initial curves, and instructions on how to pipe them. By fiddling with the code, you can either make the initial curve out of a polyline, or 7 single lines and then joining them. The last part that is supposed to pipe and mesh the curve when you are done is on the fritz and is still a work in progress. I recommend cutting it out and doing the piping and meshing yourself. You want the pipe diameter to be set so it is just barely touching itself.

The Python/Rhino code is available for download as txt file.

-E. Kidson, December 2017

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

Rostock MAX v3

Infill:

90%

Notes:

Printing the first iteration of the curve by itself is not recommended. You should print 2 at the same time if you must. The tricky part is that it this iteration doesn't have a lot of surface area that is touching the bed of the printer, so it gets ripped up while it's printing. Printing the MasterFile should make the second and third iterations come out looking reasonably nice.

Design Process

The program is pretty simple, it initiates a base curve, and then runs a for loop to construct a collage fractal. I take the initial curve and copy it 8 times while flipping and turning the pieces as I go. Once they are all in the right orientation, I add more lines to connect each piece to one another and then I join them (finding exactly where to place the line segments took some calculation). The program automatically fillets the curve. That happens as many times as you want iterations. After all this is done all one has to do is pipe and mesh the curve there.

The Concept

This was a learning experience for me to really visualize how a 3D Hilbert curve would work. In my future research, I am going to be fiddling with this concept in higher dimension and expanding the principle such that I will be able to map any dimension to any other dimension in a well-ordered way.

description.text:
Take your adventuring on the road with this new modular caravan and wagon set, which includes rolling and solid base versions of wagons with print-in-place modular harnesses and multiple canvas and gypsy toppers! This set includes multiple varieties of modular wagons, with various harnesses and accessories.   • Tongue/harness assembly for 2 draft animals with print-in-place hinge
  • Back step for wagon with printed positioning guide that glues in (optional)

Not included:

  • Rolling version of base wagon
  • Accessorized base wagons - 2 varieties, including crossbows and lantern/waterskin on the driver's seat (both rolling and solid versions)
  • Modular changeable harnesses for 1, 2 and 4 draft animals
  • Covered tops for the wagon to convert to "caravan mode" including 3 variations of the canvas-covered wagon (battle ready version with sword/shield, and road-worn version with repairs and canister), and gypsy topper with hanging lantern and lots of cool hand-sculpted wood features.

These models print with no supports, other than the harnesses which need basic slicer-created support, and paint up quickly and easily with a few base coats and a wash or two. All examples in the pics are printed @ .12 layer height.

If you like these items, please check out the full set on Hero's Hoard, and follow EC3D on Facebook where I give away premium model sets to a follower twice a month!

NOTE - all the draft animals in the pics (bear, horses, oxen) are available free in my collection HERE

description.text:
I designed this cradle for wersy's case as a way to give the controller someplace to be while doing essentially zero modification to the printer chassis. I want to add an enclosure for printing ABS and whatnot in the future, so I also wanted to avoid mounting the case in a way that would complicate that. This cradle fits right into the slot where the SD card reader used to go without blocking access to the USB port. Just print it, clean it up to your satisfaction, and you are good to go. You need to fasten your bottom panel securely if you want to prevent it from moving around too much, but that's really all there is to it. I'm sure it won't be suitable for absolutely everyone's workspace, but I hope it's a super easy option for everyone else.

I'd still like to make a few adjustments to the design in the future to make it an even easier print, but it prints alright in its current form and serves its function, so you all may as well get some use out of it in the meantime!

title: LED Campfire for Christmas crib lighting

description.text:
I'm about to refurbish old grandfathers christmas crib and thought it might be a good idea to replace the old edison-like lightbubs for lighting the fire with some modern flickering LEDs.

I salvaged a total of 16 cheap LED tea candles, each of them has a flickering LED without the need of additional electronics, running at 3V. Since I had a 12V DC adapter laying around I chained 4 of the LED's together. Having now 4 parallel sets of LED chains results in a cool irregular flickering fire effect, because each set flickers in it's own randomness.

I know it is not the smartes electric circuit, but it works well for my purpose.

I'm planning to cover the cone with some red transparent paper and stack toothpicks or small twigs around.

Watch a short clip of the LEDs in action: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gjFDCiq9lYE

Replacement spindle for the Aldi Cocoon Create Mini (Wanhao Mini) 3D printer.

The stock one on the Cocoon Create is ridiculously small (for proprietary filaments) and as a result larger 1kg spools have a nasty tendency to jerk, flap , and on long prints, fall off the spindle entirely, marring your hard work.

And so I got to digging.

Resized the I3 spindle to be printable on a Cocoon Create mini, but replaced the nut with one that will actually fit in the mut case on the printer. Works straight off the bed and will take 1kg 3DFillies, Filaform, X3D filaments and more with no more slipping spools!

Best printed vertically with thread end down. I didn't need a raft, but you will want supports touching buildplate, and remember, 100% infill so it doesn't snap! (takes about 12 hours on this printer at 100% speed)

This is a small OpenSCAD Library, which can generate quite some archimedic solids.
Missing ones can easily be extended.
For each polyeder, there are quite some "finish" options available. This changes the overall look. This Library literally creates polyeders by putting polygons together at a certain angle hierarchically. The information comes from a list with following entry
[ parend id, parent polygon side, new id, new cornernum, bend angle ]

An additional function 'angle_3poly' is provided to calculate any angle needed between polygons where 3 of them meet in a corner.

How to use ?

  • Download the polyeder.scad file
  • fill in facemode to select which face they shall have
  • fill in r_edge to define the edge cylidner radius
  • fill in r_corner to define the corner sphere radius
  • in the bottom uncomment one of the several polyeders available
  • then Press "F5" to render

How to proceed from here ?

  • place the polyeders in your own objects - maybe ornaments
  • maybe derive/extend this library. I will appreciate and publish any fix. Currenty antiprism is broken.
  • ... and if you are happy with the lib, consider donating me a tip ...

description.text:
This ball mill was made for grinding sand and cleaning objects like rusty bolts. It works but takes a very long time to grind sand down, this is because of the size of the balls are too small. Getting larger balls will help.
Some professionals that design and manufacture mill for industry helped in the design of the lifter and the correct speed for milling. The professionals were interested in how long it would take for the lining of the mill to be worn out. This is yet to be tested.
http://tinkersprojects.com/project/3d-printed-ball-mill/

see more what I have done: http://tinkersprojects.com/

Operation:

After powering the mill with 12V DC power, settings can be seen/changed using the LCD and can be altered using the 3 buttons (up, down and enter). Speed and duration are the 2 settings that can be set to control the mill. While the mill is in operation, the LCD will display the current speed and the time left of milling. By pressing the enter button, the mill will stop.

parts list:

1 x controller, PLEX or Arduino UNO (see below for more details)
1 x photo interupt
2 x 20mm M3 srew
2 x 20mm M3 srew
1 x 100mm M8 bolt
2 x 60mm M8 bolt
4 x M8 nut
4 x 608 bearing
1 x 12V 688RPM 9Kg.cm geared DC motor, part no.:JGB37-550 (https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Free-Shipping-12V-688RPM-9Kg-cm-high-power-High-torque-miniature-dc-gear-motor-motors-JGB37/32776724375.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.JbnZ7R)
4 x rubber feet
100 x 6mm-10mm ball bearings

Controller:

The controller used is the PLEX board from plexcontroller.com (an Arduino UNO can be used instead). The controller Uses a 16x2 LCD and buttons inputs to set settings display speed/timer while in operation. A photo interrupt and encoder are used to calculate the speed of the mill to be compared to the set speed. This comparison is analyzed and an output is used to control a MOSFET for the motor.
http://tinkersprojects.com/project/3d-printed-ball-mill/

NOTE:

A diode and capacitor were used to block current drawn from the controller to the DC motor. If not used the controller will rest.

title: PruLight - LED light for any Prusa i3 frame

description.text:
The PruLight is meant to be used with (USB) LED strips. The light bar can be turned to change the angle at what needs to be lid.

Cheap LED strips usually don't stick well which is why I added friction fit "clipper" clips to keep the strips inside the light bar. The "corner" pieces aren't strictly necessary but will add friction to keep the lighting angle in the chosen position. Be sure to watch out for the cable slot when installing the light and please use 10mm velcro strips for cable management.

The camera mount should work for most action cameras but had been modelled with the SQ11 in mind for which I will upload the camera mount separately. Use M5-25 hex head screws and M5 hex nuts to populate "screw" and "nut" of the camera mount. The SQ11mount also exists as a solo thing.

There is also a version of this arm for the Creality CR-10 - CreaLight - and probably many other printers based on open-frame v-slot extruded aluminum bars. The version for the Creality Ender 2 - EnLight - is slightly different but based on the same idea.

I might add shorter and longer light bars in the future.

The arms are known to fit on the frames of the Original Prusa i3 MK2/MK2s as well as MK3.

The light bar as well as all the other parts work well with default settings for 0.1mm layer height but can tend to get a bit tight at 0.2mm height or more.

As easy as 1, 2, 3

Just put a USB LED strip with the USB cable oriented towards the cable slot into the light bar and carefully cut it to lengths. Then remove the protection and glue it to the light bar. Add the corner pieces to the corners and two clippers about equally spaced apart from each other to keep the LED strip in place. Be sure to not cover LEDs or electric components but just the strip/tape instead.

In case your LED strip is not flat but a few mm heigh be sure to clip the clippers to length.

Use 10mm velcro for cable management.
